{"title_page": "Xplore Dundee", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2015}}\n{{Infobox Bus transit\n|name            = Xplore Dundee\n|logo            = XploreDundee.png\n|image           = Xplore Dundeee Enviro400 in green livery 2019.jpg\n|image size      =\n|image_caption   = An Enviro400 in the current green livery \n|parent          = [[National Express]]\n|founded         = 1997\n|headquarters    = [[Dundee]]\n|locale          =\n|service_area    =\n|service_type    = Bus services\n|destinations    =\n|fleet           = 117\n|ceo             = Christine McGlasson\n|website         = [http://www.nxbus.co.uk/dundee]\n}} \n\n'''Xplore Dundee (formerly branded as '''National Express Dundee''') is a bus operator based in [[Dundee]], Scotland operating services mainly within Dundee City. It is a subsidiary of [[National Express]].\n\n==History==\n{{see also|Dundee Corporation Tramways}}\n\nThe company has its origins in the Dundee and District Tramways Company, which commenced horse tram operations on 30 August 1877. Steam traction was adopted in 1885. On 1 June 1899, the company was compulsorily acquired by the local municipality to become Dundee City Tramways, which was electrified between 1900 and 1902.\n\nFrom 1922, motor buses began to be operated in addition to the trams. The tram system continued to be extended until 1933. But by 1956, the trams had been fully replaced by buses and the company renamed Dundee Corporation Transport.\n\n[[Local Government (Scotland) Act 1973|Local government reorganisation]] meant that the bus operation passed to [[Tayside]] Regional Council in May 1975. In spite of the change of name, the council's bus operations were confined to the Dundee area. The livery was changed from green to dark blue, light blue and white.\n\nIn preparation for [[bus deregulation in the United Kingdom|bus deregulation]] in October 1986 it was restructured into a separate legal entity.\n\nTravel Dundee Limited formerly Tayside Bus Company Limited</ref> and in 1991 sold in a [[management buy out]]. In February 1997 it was sold to [[National Express]] and rebranded Travel Dundee. The livery changed again, this time to blue, red and white.\n\n[[Image:Travel Dundee logo.png|thumb|right|250px|Travel Dundee logo, 1997\u20132008]]\n\nTravel Greyhound was the coaching subsidiary which offered a range of coaches and buses for hire. Greyhound Luxury Coaches used to be a trading name for TD Alexander and Sons who commenced operations in 1960. The business was acquired by Tayside Public Transport on 13 August 1990, and re-branded Tayside Greyhound. The Greyhound brand is no longer in use.\n\nTravel Dundee had been a contractor to [[Scottish Citylink]] form many years. However, shortly after the formation of a joint venture between Citylink and [[Stagecoach Group|Stagecoach]] in November 2005, Travel Dundee's services ceased. They were reinstated at short notice from 9 January 2006 when extra journeys were added to route M91 from [[Perth, Scotland|Perth]] direct to [[Edinburgh]]. In May 2006, Travel Dundee commenced operating journeys on route M90 Perth - [[Kinross]] - [[Dunfermline]] - Edinburgh. Citylink ceased for the third time in September 2008, as part of a review of coaching activities.\n<ref>Dundee Area Bus Directory, Second Edition - Spring 2009, by Susanna Scott. {{ISSN|2041-0735}}</ref>\n\n[[Image:NXDundee.svg|thumb|right|250px|National Express Dundee logo, 2008\u20132015]]\nIn November 2007 National Express announced plans to re-brand all of their operations under a new unified National Express identity with Travel Dundee rebranded as National Express Dundee in October 2008.\n\nIn June 2015, it was announced that the business would be rebranded as Xplore Dundee with a green livery resembling that of Dundee Corporation Transport introduced. The rebrand occurred on 11 September 2015.\n\n==Fare structure==\nThe single fares were previously calculated according to the number of fare stages that you pass through with fares split into three categories 1 stage, 2-3 stages or 4+ stages. Now short hop fares (valid for one fare stage) and max singles (two or more fare stages) are used for single journeys. There are discounts for children and young people.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nxbus.co.uk/dundee/tickets-prices|title=Xplore Dundee Tickets and Prices|last=|first=|date=|website=nxbus.co.uk|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-10}}</ref>\n\nA range of multi-use fares are available including daysavers and their own travelcards which are available for 1-week, 4-week and 52-week periods of validity. Group and evening tickets are also available. Contactless payments were introduced in 2019, and discounts are in place for customers purchasing m-tickets on the Xplore Dundee app. \n\n==Routes==\nThe company operates a number of urban routes, their numbering system has similarities to other National Express UK Bus subsidiaries with school routes indicated with the suffix - S, the use of suffix letters - A, B, C and D, as well as the use of the prefix.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nxbus.co.uk/routes/dundee/|title=Dundee Bus Routes {{!}} Information {{!}} National Express Xplore Dundee|website=nxbus.co.uk|access-date=2019-11-10}}</ref>\n\n==Vehicle types==\n[[File:National Express Dundee bus 7002 (SP54 CHG), 31 March 2014.jpg|thumb|right|National Express Dundee liveried [[Wright Eclipse Gemini]] bodied [[Volvo B7TL]] in 2014]]\nXplore Dundee have a fleet of 115 single and double decker buses, most being from [[Volvo]]. Some vehicles have come from other National Express operators in the West Midlands and from the now sold operation in London.{{cn|date=February 2019}}\n\nFrom 1997 to 1999, shortly after National Express took over, Travel Dundee received 30 [[Wright Liberator]] bodied [[Volvo B10L]]s and 25 [[Wright Renown]] bodied [[Volvo B10BLE]]s. In 2004, the fleet was upgraded with 18 new [[Wright Eclipse Gemini]] double-deckers.{{cn|date=February 2019}}\n\nXplore Dundee, then National Express Dundee, bought 29 new [[Wright Eclipse Urban|Wright Eclipse Urban 2]]-bodied [[Volvo B7RLE]] in 2011 and 2012 which were used to replace older vehicles.{{cn|date=February 2019}}\n\nIn 2013, the company received its first nine [[Alexander Dennis Enviro 400]] hybrid buses, partly funded by the Scottish Government Green Bus Fund.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thecourier.co.uk/news/local/dundee/bosses-buzzing-after-dundee-takes-delivery-of-electric-buses-1.84559|title=Bosses buzzing after Dundee takes delivery of electric buses - The Courier|date=16 April 2013|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, 14 brand new [[Alexander Dennis Enviro400 MMC]] buses arrived to operate on route 22. These buses are branded ''Emerald'' and have USB ports and free Wi-Fi onboard.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nxbus.co.uk/dundee/news/emerald-your-new-22|title=Emerald: Your New 22 {{!}} News {{!}} National Express Xplore Dundee|website=nxbus.co.uk|access-date=2019-11-10}}</ref> These were introduced on 2 December 2018, with a follow-up order of 9 announced in November 2019.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.eveningtelegraph.co.uk/fp/new-fleet-of-low-emission-xplore-buses-to-arrive-in-dundee-next-year/|title=New fleet of low-emission Xplore buses to arrive in Dundee next year|work=Evening Telegraph|access-date=2019-11-10|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\n\n==Subsidiary companies==\n===Travel Wishart===\nTravel Wishart provides rural bus and coach services in the county of [[Angus, Scotland|Angus]], from its base in [[Friockheim]]. The operation previously traded  as G&N Wishart and was the last remaining division of National Express in the ''Travel'' series of brands. In 2013, the Travel Wishart operating licence was sold to new owners. It operated a fleet mainly used for coach day-trips.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.travelwishart.co.uk/|title=Travel Wishart|access-date=28 April 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130525015331/http://travelwishart.co.uk/|archive-date=25 May 2013|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Xplore More===\nXplore More (previously branded as NXDiscovrit) operates coach trips and excursions,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.xploremore.co.uk/#|title=Xplore More Coach Hire|website=www.xploremore.co.uk|access-date=2019-11-10}}</ref> as well as the X90 Dundee to Edinburgh Airport Express service, which was launched in Summer 2019.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.eveningtelegraph.co.uk/fp/xplore-dundee-launches-direct-service-from-dundee-to-edinburgh-airport/|title=Xplore Dundee launches direct bus service between Dundee and Edinburgh Airport|work=Evening Telegraph|access-date=2019-11-10|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Travel Dundee (bus company)|National Express Dundee}}\n* [http://nxbus.co.uk/dundee/ Xplore Dundee website]\n\n{{Dundee}}\n{{NEXG}}\n{{Bus operators in Scotland}}\n\n[[Category:Bus operators in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Transport in Dundee]]\n[[Category:National Express companies]]\n[[Category:Tayside]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2015}}\n{{Infobox Bus transit\n|name            = Xplore Dundee\n|logo            = XploreDundee.png\n|image           = Xplore Dundeee Enviro400 in green livery 2019.jpg\n|image size      =\n|image_caption   = An Enviro400 in the current green livery \n|parent          = [[National Express]]\n|founded         = 1997\n|headquarters    = [[Dundee]]\n|locale          =\n|service_area    =\n|service_type    = Bus services\n|destinations    =\n|fleet           = 117\n|ceo             = Christine McGlasson\n|website         = [http://www.nxbus.co.uk/dundee/ www.nxbus.co.uk/dundee]\n}} \n\n'''Xplore Dundee'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nxbus.co.uk/dundee/|title=National Express Xplore Dundee|website=nxbus.co.uk}}</ref> (formerly branded as '''National Express Dundee''') is a bus operator based in [[Dundee]], Scotland operating services mainly within Dundee City. It is a subsidiary of [[National Express]].\n\n==History==\n{{see also|Dundee Corporation Tramways}}\n\nThe company has its origins in the Dundee and District Tramways Company, which commenced horse tram operations on 30 August 1877. Steam traction was adopted in 1885. On 1 June 1899, the company was compulsorily acquired by the local municipality to become Dundee City Tramways, which was electrified between 1900 and 1902.\n\nFrom 1922, motor buses began to be operated in addition to the trams. The tram system continued to be extended until 1933. But by 1956, the trams had been fully replaced by buses and the company renamed Dundee Corporation Transport.<ref>{{cite news|title=\u2018Dundee\u2019s trams era was magical\u2019|url=https://www.eveningtelegraph.co.uk/fp/dundees-trams-era-magical/|accessdate=10 September 2017|publisher=[[Evening Telegraph (Dundee)|Evening Telegraph]]|date=14 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n[[Local Government (Scotland) Act 1973|Local government reorganisation]] meant that the bus operation passed to [[Tayside]] Regional Council in May 1975. In spite of the change of name, the council's bus operations were confined to the Dundee area.<ref>David G Wilson, ''Buses of Eastern Scotland'' 2nd edition Manchester 1981</ref> The livery was changed from green to dark blue, light blue and white.\n\nIn preparation for [[bus deregulation in the United Kingdom|bus deregulation]] in October 1986 it was restructured into a separate legal entity<ref name=SC098156>[http://data.companieshouse.gov.uk/doc/company/SC098156 Companies House extract company no SC098156] Travel Dundee Limited formerly Tayside Bus Company Limited</ref> and in 1991 sold in a [[management buy out]]. In February 1997 it was sold to [[National Express]] and rebranded Travel Dundee.<ref>Stewart J Brown, ''Buses in Britain'', London, 1993</ref><ref>Peter White, ''Bus and coach deregulation and privatization in Great Britain, with particular reference to Scotland'', ''Journal of Transport Geography'', Vol. 6, No. 2, pp. 135-141, 1998</ref> The livery changed again, this time to blue, red and white.\n\n[[Image:Travel Dundee logo.png|thumb|right|250px|Travel Dundee logo, 1997\u20132008]]\nTravel Greyhound was the coaching subsidiary which offered a range of coaches and buses for hire. Greyhound Luxury Coaches used to be a trading name for TD Alexander and Sons,<ref>[http://data.companieshouse.gov.uk/doc/company/SC037778 Companies House extract company no SC037778] TD Alexander and Sons (Scotland) Limited</ref> who commenced operations in 1960. The business was acquired by Tayside Public Transport on 13 August 1990, and re-branded Tayside Greyhound. The Greyhound brand is no longer in use.<ref>D J Slater, ''Major PSV Operators 4: Scotland and Ireland'' Birmingham 1991</ref>\n\nTravel Dundee had been a contractor to [[Scottish Citylink]] form many years. However, shortly after the formation of a joint venture between Citylink and [[Stagecoach Group|Stagecoach]] in November 2005, Travel Dundee's services ceased. They were reinstated at short notice from 9 January 2006 when extra journeys were added to route M91 from [[Perth, Scotland|Perth]] direct to [[Edinburgh]]. In May 2006, Travel Dundee commenced operating journeys on route M90 Perth - [[Kinross]] - [[Dunfermline]] - Edinburgh. Citylink ceased for the third time in September 2008, as part of a review of coaching activities.\n<ref>Dundee Area Bus Directory, Second Edition - Spring 2009, by Susanna Scott. {{ISSN|2041-0735}}</ref>\n\n[[Image:NXDundee.svg|thumb|right|250px|National Express Dundee logo, 2008\u20132015]]\nIn November 2007 National Express announced plans to re-brand all of their operations under a new unified National Express identity<ref>[http://www.nationalexpressgroup.com/media/corporatenews.aspx?newsyear=2007&newsitem=66 New Identity for National Express Group] National Express corporate news 15 November 2007</ref> with Travel Dundee rebranded as National Express Dundee in October 2008.\n\nIn June 2015, it was announced that the business would be rebranded as Xplore Dundee with a green livery resembling that of Dundee Corporation Transport introduced.<ref>[http://nxbus.co.uk/dundee/news/its-a-fresh-new-look-for-dundee It's a fresh new look for Dundee's green bus company] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150905045702/http://nxbus.co.uk/dundee/news/its-a-fresh-new-look-for-dundee |date=5 September 2015 }} National Express Dundee 27 June 2015</ref><ref>\"Xplore Dundee\" ''[[Coach & Bus Week]]'' issue 1198 15 July 2015 page 7</ref><ref>\"National Express Dundee\" ''[[Buses Magazine|Buses]]'' issue 725 August 2015 page 85</ref><ref>\"National Express takes Dundee back to the early 1970s\" ''Buses'' issue 726 September 2015 page 7</ref> The rebrand occurred on 11 September 2015.\n\n==Fare structure==\nThe single fares were previously calculated according to the number of fare stages that you pass through with fares split into three categories 1 stage, 2-3 stages or 4+ stages. Now short hop fares (valid for one fare stage) and max singles (two or more fare stages) are used for single journeys. There are discounts for children and young people.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nxbus.co.uk/dundee/tickets-prices|title=Xplore Dundee Tickets and Prices|last=|first=|date=|website=nxbus.co.uk|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-10}}</ref>\n\nA range of multi-use fares are available including daysavers and their own travelcards which are available for 1-week, 4-week and 52-week periods of validity. Group and evening tickets are also available. Contactless payments were introduced in 2019, and discounts are in place for customers purchasing m-tickets on the Xplore Dundee app. \n\n==Routes==\nThe company operates a number of urban routes, their numbering system has similarities to other National Express UK Bus subsidiaries with school routes indicated with the suffix - S, the use of suffix letters - A, B, C and D, as well as the use of the prefix.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nxbus.co.uk/routes/dundee/|title=Dundee Bus Routes {{!}} Information {{!}} National Express Xplore Dundee|website=nxbus.co.uk|access-date=2019-11-10}}</ref>\n\n==Vehicle types==\n[[File:National Express Dundee bus 7002 (SP54 CHG), 31 March 2014.jpg|thumb|right|National Express Dundee liveried [[Wright Eclipse Gemini]] bodied [[Volvo B7TL]] in 2014]]\nXplore Dundee have a fleet of 115 single and double decker buses, most being from [[Volvo]]. Some vehicles have come from other National Express operators in the West Midlands and from the now sold operation in London.{{cn|date=February 2019}}\n\nFrom 1997 to 1999, shortly after National Express took over, Travel Dundee received 30 [[Wright Liberator]] bodied [[Volvo B10L]]s and 25 [[Wright Renown]] bodied [[Volvo B10BLE]]s. In 2004, the fleet was upgraded with 18 new [[Wright Eclipse Gemini]] double-deckers.{{cn|date=February 2019}}\n\nXplore Dundee, then National Express Dundee, bought 29 new [[Wright Eclipse Urban|Wright Eclipse Urban 2]]-bodied [[Volvo B7RLE]] in 2011 and 2012 which were used to replace older vehicles.{{cn|date=February 2019}}\n\nIn 2013, the company received its first nine [[Alexander Dennis Enviro 400]] hybrid buses, partly funded by the Scottish Government Green Bus Fund.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thecourier.co.uk/news/local/dundee/bosses-buzzing-after-dundee-takes-delivery-of-electric-buses-1.84559|title=Bosses buzzing after Dundee takes delivery of electric buses - The Courier|date=16 April 2013|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, 14 brand new [[Alexander Dennis Enviro400 MMC]] buses arrived to operate on route 22. These buses are branded ''Emerald'' and have USB ports and free Wi-Fi onboard.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nxbus.co.uk/dundee/news/emerald-your-new-22|title=Emerald: Your New 22 {{!}} News {{!}} National Express Xplore Dundee|website=nxbus.co.uk|access-date=2019-11-10}}</ref> These were introduced on 2 December 2018, with a follow-up order of 9 announced in November 2019.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.eveningtelegraph.co.uk/fp/new-fleet-of-low-emission-xplore-buses-to-arrive-in-dundee-next-year/|title=New fleet of low-emission Xplore buses to arrive in Dundee next year|work=Evening Telegraph|access-date=2019-11-10|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\n\n==Subsidiary companies==\n===Travel Wishart===\nTravel Wishart provides rural bus and coach services in the county of [[Angus, Scotland|Angus]], from its base in [[Friockheim]]. The operation previously traded  as G&N Wishart and was the last remaining division of National Express in the ''Travel'' series of brands. In 2013, the Travel Wishart operating licence was sold to new owners. It operated a fleet mainly used for coach day-trips.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.travelwishart.co.uk/|title=Travel Wishart|access-date=28 April 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130525015331/http://travelwishart.co.uk/|archive-date=25 May 2013|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Xplore More===\nXplore More (previously branded as NXDiscovrit) operates coach trips and excursions,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.xploremore.co.uk/#|title=Xplore More Coach Hire|website=www.xploremore.co.uk|access-date=2019-11-10}}</ref> as well as the X90 Dundee to Edinburgh Airport Express service, which was launched in Summer 2019.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.eveningtelegraph.co.uk/fp/xplore-dundee-launches-direct-service-from-dundee-to-edinburgh-airport/|title=Xplore Dundee launches direct bus service between Dundee and Edinburgh Airport|work=Evening Telegraph|access-date=2019-11-10|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Travel Dundee (bus company)|National Express Dundee}}\n* [http://nxbus.co.uk/dundee/ Xplore Dundee website]\n\n{{Dundee}}\n{{NEXG}}\n{{Bus operators in Scotland}}\n\n[[Category:Bus operators in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Transport in Dundee]]\n[[Category:National Express companies]]\n[[Category:Tayside]]\n", "name_user": "Dgmitchell91", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eHistory:Teaked info but put back in if you feel it needs to be there)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Xplore_Dundee"}
{"title_page": "Lucia Lucas", "text_new": "{{distinguish|Lucie Lucas}}\n{{COI|date=December 2019}}\n[[File:Lucas.L.Headshot.jpg|alt=|thumb|Lucia Lucas (2019)]]\n'''Lucia Lucas''' (born c. 1980){{citation needed|date=December 2019}} is an American [[transgender]] [[baritone]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/lucia-lucas-transgender-opera-singer_n_5ccb699ee4b0d123955094c0|title=Transgender Opera Singer Makes US Debut in ''Don Giovanni''|date=2019-05-02|website=[[HuffPost]]|access-date=2019-10-05}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/lucia-lucas-the-transgender-female-baritone-who-will-sing-at-the-coliseum-dfgr7dmtz|title=Lucia Lucas, the transgender female baritone who will sing at the Coliseum|last=Fisher|first=Neil|date=2 October 2019|newspaper=[[The Times]]|access-date=5 October 2019}}</ref> She made history when, in March, 2018, it was announced that she would become the first female (transgender) baritone to perform a principal role on an American operatic stage.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/feature/nbc-out/transgender-opera-singer-make-u-s-history-oklahoma-n851951|title=Transgender opera singer to make U.S. history \u2014 in Oklahoma|website=NBC News}}</ref> The performance on May 3, 2019, in Tulsa, Oklahoma, saw Lucas playing the starring role in Mozart's ''[[Don Giovanni]]'' with the [[Tulsa Opera]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2019/apr/30/don-giovanni-trans-opera-singer-lucia-lucas|title='This opens doors': Trans woman to play Don Giovanni in a first for US opera|first=Chloe|last=Veltman|date=May 1, 2019|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/11/arts/music/transgender-opera-singers.html|title=Transgender Opera Singers Find Their Voices|first=Michael|last=Cooper|date=July 11, 2019|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref> The performance is the subject of the 2020 feature documentary ''The Sound of Identity'', directed by [[James Kicklighter]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kqed.org/news/11773585/sacramento-opera-star-lucia-lucas-pushes-industry-boundaries-and-beyond|title=Sacramento Opera Star Lucia Lucas Pushes Industry Boundaries \u2014 and Beyond|date=2019-09-15|website=KQED|language=en-us|access-date=2019-12-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.broadwayworld.com/bwwopera/article/LUCIAS-VOICE-Documentary-to-Feature-First-Transgender-Lead-in-US-Opera-2019041037|title=LUCIA'S VOICE Documentary To Feature First Transgender Lead In U.S. Opera|last=Desk|first=BWW News|website=BroadwayWorld.com|language=en|access-date=2019-12-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jameskicklighter.com/project/lucias-voice-lucia-lucas-documentary|title=Lucia's Voice|website=Director James Kicklighter|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-29}}</ref>\n\nSubsequently, Lucas became the first transgender baritone to appear with the [[English National Opera]] in London on 5 October 2019, playing Public Opinion in ''[[Orpheus in the Underworld]]'' at the [[London Coliseum]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/av/entertainment-arts-49943671/lucia-lucas-making-uk-operatic-debut-at-the-eno |title=Lucia Lucas: Making UK operatic debut at the ENO |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=5 October 2019 |accessdate=5 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nLucas grew up in [[Sacramento, California]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://radio.rte.ie/radio1highlights/traditional-puberty-testosterone-high-voice-will-drop-no-way-go-way/|title='If you have traditional puberty... the testosterone is high, the voice will drop. But there is no way to go the other way.' \u2013 RT\u00c9 Radio 1 Highlights|website=radio.rte.ie|access-date=2019-11-02}}</ref> She studied [[Horn (instrument)|horn]] and voice at [[California State University, Sacramento]] and then did graduate work at the [[Chicago College of Performing Arts]]. She moved to Germany in 2009. She decided to [[Transitioning (transgender)|transition]] in November 2013, started taking [[Estrogen (medication)|estrogen]] and [[antiandrogen]]s in July 2014 and underwent [[facial feminization surgery]] in September. In 2016, she had her [[gender reassignment surgery]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nLucia Lucas married Ariana Lucas in 2009.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rte.ie/radio/radioplayer/html5/#/radio1/21133658|title=Lucia Lucas Transgender Opera Singer|last=|first=|date=|website=www.rte.ie|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-02}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lucas, Lucia}}\n[[Category:1980s births]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American operatic baritones]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Sacramento, California]]\n[[Category:Transgender and transsexual women]]\n[[Category:LGBT singers from the United States]]\n\n\n{{US-singer-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{distinguish|Lucie Lucas}}\n{{COI|date=December 2019}}\n[[File:Lucas.L.Headshot.jpg|alt=|thumb|Lucia Lucas (2019)]]\n'''Lucia Lucas''' (born c. 1980){{citation needed|date=December 2019}} is an American [[transgender]] [[baritone]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/lucia-lucas-transgender-opera-singer_n_5ccb699ee4b0d123955094c0|title=Transgender Opera Singer Makes US Debut in ''Don Giovanni''|date=2019-05-02|website=[[HuffPost]]|access-date=2019-10-05}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/lucia-lucas-the-transgender-female-baritone-who-will-sing-at-the-coliseum-dfgr7dmtz|title=Lucia Lucas, the transgender female baritone who will sing at the Coliseum|last=Fisher|first=Neil|date=2 October 2019|newspaper=[[The Times]]|access-date=5 October 2019}}</ref> She made history when, in March, 2018, it was announced that she would become the first female (transgender) baritone to perform a principal role on an American operatic stage.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/feature/nbc-out/transgender-opera-singer-make-u-s-history-oklahoma-