ebut-at-the-eno |title=Lucia Lucas: Making UK operatic debut at the ENO |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=5 October 2019 |accessdate=5 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nLucas grew up in [[Sacramento, California]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://radio.rte.ie/radio1highlights/traditional-puberty-testosterone-high-voice-will-drop-no-way-go-way/|title='If you have traditional puberty... the testosterone is high, the voice will drop. But there is no way to go the other way.' \u2013 RT\u00c9 Radio 1 Highlights|website=radio.rte.ie|access-date=2019-11-02}}</ref> She studied [[Horn (instrument)|horn]] and voice at [[California State University, Sacramento]] and then did graduate work at the [[Chicago College of Performing Arts]]. She moved to Germany in 2009. She decided to [[Transitioning (transgender)|transition]] in November 2013, started taking [[Estrogen (medication)|estrogen]] and [[Antiandrogen|antiandrogens]] in July 2014 and underwent [[facial feminization surgery]] in September. In 2016, she had her [[gender reassignment surgery]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nLucia Lucas married Ariana Lucas in 2009.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rte.ie/radio/radioplayer/html5/#/radio1/21133658|title=Lucia Lucas Transgender Opera Singer|last=|first=|date=|website=www.rte.ie|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-02}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lucas, Lucia}}\n[[Category:1980s births]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American operatic baritones]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Sacramento, California]]\n[[Category:Transgender and transsexual women]]\n[[Category:LGBT singers from the United States]]\n\n{{US-singer-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lucia_Lucas"}
{"title_page": "Lu Jinhua", "text_new": "{{short description|Chinese opera performer}}\n{{more citations needed|date=January 2019}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n|name=Lu Jinhua\n|birth_name=Ke Wenqi\n|birth_date={{birth date|1927|2|25}}\n|birth_place=[[Shanghai]], [[Republic of China (1912\u20131949)|Republic of China]]\n|death_date={{death date and age|2018|1|10|1927|2|25}}\n|death_place=[[Los Angeles metropolitan area]], [[California]], U.S.\n|spouse=Yang Defang (\u6768\u5fb7\u82b3)\n|children=\n}}\n{{Chinese name|Lu}}\n'''Lu Jinhua''' (25 February 1927 \u2013 10 January 2018) was a Chinese [[Yue opera]] artist who played ''[[Sheng (Chinese opera)|Sheng]]'' roles. She starred in the 1958 Yue opera film ''[[A Test of Love (1958 film)|A Test of Love]]'' alongside [[Fu Quanxiang]].\n\nLu Jinhua founded the Shaozhuang Troupe with [[Wang Wenjuan]] in 1947. She is considered the founder of the Lu school.\n\n==References==\n*{{cite web|url=http://xmwb.xinmin.cn/html/2018-01/12/content_14_4.htm|title=\u8d8a\u5267\u540d\u5bb6\u9646\u9526\u82b1\u5728\u7f8e\u53bb\u4e16|date=2018-01-12|newspaper=[[Xinmin Evening News]]|last=Wang Jianhong (\u738b\u5251\u8679)|language=zh|trans-title=Famous Yue opera artist Lu Jinhua passes away in the U.S.}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1927 births]]\n[[Category:2018 deaths]]\n[[Category:Yue opera actresses]]\n[[Category:20th-century Chinese singers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Chinese actresses]]\n[[Category:Chinese film actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Shanghai]]\n[[Category:Singers from Shanghai]]\n[[Category:Cross-gender actresses]]\n\n\n{{China-actor-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Chinese opera performer}}\n{{more citations needed|date=January 2019}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n|name=Lu Jinhua\n|birth_name=Ke Wenqi\n|birth_date={{birth date|1927|2|25}}\n|birth_place=[[Shanghai]], [[Republic of China (1912\u20131949)|Republic of China]]\n|death_date={{death date and age|2018|1|10|1927|2|25}}\n|death_place=[[Los Angeles metropolitan area]], [[California]], U.S.\n|spouse=Yang Defang (\u6768\u5fb7\u82b3)\n|children=\n}}\n{{Chinese name|Lu}}\n'''Lu Jinhua''' (25 February 1927 \u2013 10 January 2018) was a Chinese [[Yue opera]] artist who played ''[[Sheng (Chinese opera)|Sheng]]'' roles. She starred in the 1958 Yue opera film ''[[A Test of Love (1958 film)|A Test of Love]]'' alongside [[Fu Quanxiang]].\n\nLu Jinhua founded the Shaozhuang Troupe with [[Wang Wenjuan]] in 1947. She is considered the founder of the Lu school.\n\n==References==\n*{{cite web|url=http://xmwb.xinmin.cn/html/2018-01/12/content_14_4.htm|title=\u8d8a\u5267\u540d\u5bb6\u9646\u9526\u82b1\u5728\u7f8e\u53bb\u4e16|date=2018-01-12|newspaper=[[Xinmin Evening News]]|last=Wang Jianhong (\u738b\u5251\u8679)|language=zh|trans-title=Famous Yue opera artist Lu Jinhua passes away in the U.S.}}\n\n[[Category:1927 births]]\n[[Category:2018 deaths]]\n[[Category:Yue opera actresses]]\n[[Category:20th-century Chinese singers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Chinese actresses]]\n[[Category:Chinese film actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Shanghai]]\n[[Category:Singers from Shanghai]]\n[[Category:Cross-gender actresses]]\n\n\n{{China-actor-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lu_Jinhua"}
{"title_page": "Todd Haley", "text_new": "{{short description|American football coach}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox NFL biography\n| name           = Todd Haley\n| image          = Todd Haley.jpg\n| image_size     = 240\n| alt            = Haley wearing a red Kansas City Chiefs sweatshirt and red Chiefs visor while autographing a Chiefs baseball cap\n| caption        = Haley with the Chiefs in 2009\n| current_team   = \n| position       =\n| birth_date     = {{Birth date and age|1967|2|28|mf=y}}\n| birth_place    = [[Atlanta, Georgia]]\n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n| high_school    = [[Upper St. Clair High School|Upper St. Clair]]<br>([[Upper St. Clair Township, Allegheny County, Pennsylvania|Upper St. Clair, Pennsylvania]])\n| college        = [[University of North Florida|North Florida]]\n| pastcoaching   = \n* [[New York Jets]] (1995\u20131996)<br>Scouting assistant\n* New York Jets (1997\u20132000)<br>Wide receivers coach\n* [[Chicago Bears]] (2001\u20132003)<br>Wide receivers coach\n* [[Dallas Cowboys]] (2004\u20132006)<br>Wide receivers coach\n* [[Arizona Cardinals]] (2007\u20132008)<br>Offensive coordinator\n* [[Kansas City Chiefs]] (2009\u20132011)<br>Head coach\n* [[Pittsburgh Steelers]] (2012\u20132017)<br>Offensive coordinator\n* [[Cleveland Browns]] (2018)<br>Offensive coordinator\n* [[Riverview High School (Sarasota, Florida)|Riverview High School]] (2020\u2013present)<br>Offensive coordinator\n| highlights     = \n| regular_record = {{Winning percentage|19|26|record=y}}\n| playoff_record = {{Winning percentage|0|1|record=y}}\n| overall_record = {{Winning percentage|19|27|record=y}}\n| pfrcoach       = HaleTo0\n}}\n\n'''Todd Haley''' (born February 28, 1967) was a pitiful [[American football]] coach who is the offensive coordinator for the [[Riverview High School (Sarasota, Florida)|Riverview High School]] football team. From 1997 to 2006, he had stints as the [[wide receiver]]s coach of the [[New York Jets]], [[Chicago Bears]], and [[Dallas Cowboys]]. He served as the offensive coordinator of the [[Arizona Cardinals]] from 2007 to 2008, the head coach of the [[Kansas City Chiefs]] from 2009 to 2011, the offensive coordinator of the [[Pittsburgh Steelers]] from 2012 to 2017, and the offensive coordinator of the [[Cleveland Browns]] in 2018, but he was fired in Week 8 of his first season with the team following a loss to his previous team, the Pittsburgh Steelers.\n\n==Early years==\nHaley was born on February 28, 1967, in [[Atlanta, Georgia]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Todd Haley named Kansas City Chiefs head coach |url=http://kcchiefs.com/news/2009/02/06/todd_haley_named_kansas_city_chiefs_head_coach/ |publisher=Kansas City Chiefs |date=February 6, 2009 |accessdate=February 6, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090209090923/http://kcchiefs.com/news/2009/02/06/todd_haley_named_kansas_city_chiefs_head_coach |archivedate=February 9, 2009 }}</ref> He is the son of [[Dick Haley]], formerly Director of Player Personnel for the Pittsburgh Steelers and New York Jets and also a former NFL cornerback.<ref name=\"Haley named\">{{cite web | title=Todd Haley named Kansas City Chiefs head coach |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090303204702/http://kcchiefs.com/news/2009/02/06/todd_haley_named_kansas_city_chiefs_head_coach |archivedate=March 3, 2009| url=http://kcchiefs.com/news/2009/02/06/todd_haley_named_kansas_city_chiefs_head_coach/ | publisher=Kansas City Chiefs | date=February 6, 2009 | accessdate=February 6, 2009}}</ref>\n\nAs a youth, Haley was a ball boy for the Steelers and attended Steelers training camps with his father.<ref name=\"Haley named\"/> Alongside his father, Haley would watch the Steelers' game and practice film.<ref name=\"Haley named\"/><ref name=\"new Chief in town\">{{cite web | title=Todd Haley is the new Chief in town | url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2009/writers/peter_king/02/06/chiefs/index.html | last=King | first=Peter | publisher=Sports Illustrated | date=February 6, 2009 | accessdate=February 6, 2009}}</ref> While his family was located in [[Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania]] for his father's profession, Haley attended [[Upper St. Clair High School]].<ref name=\"Haley named\"/> He went on to attend the [[University of Florida]] and [[University of Miami]], playing on the two schools' respective golf squads.<ref name=\"Haley named\"/> Haley graduated from the [[University of North Florida]] in 1991 with a bachelor's degree in communication.<ref name=\"Haley named\"/>\n\n==Coaching career==\n===New York Jets===\nHaley was hired by the New York Jets in 1995 and served as an assistant in the scouting department for two seasons. At the time, Haley's father Dick was working with the Jets as Director of Player Personnel.<ref name=\"new Chief in town\"/> In 1997, he was promoted to offensive assistant/quality control coach and worked closely with then-offensive coordinator [[Charlie Weis]]. From 1999 to 2000 Haley was the Jets' wide receivers coach, helping [[Keyshawn Johnson]] make his second [[Pro Bowl]] appearance. During his tenure with the Jets, Haley began his association with [[Scott Pioli]], who served as Director of Pro Personnel for the Jets from 1997 to 1999. Pioli later became the general manager of the Kansas City Chiefs and hired Haley as the team's head coach in 2009.\n\n===Chicago Bears===\nIn 2001, Haley joined the Chicago Bears as  wide receivers coach and served in the position until 2003.\n\n===Dallas Cowboys===\nFrom 2004 to 2006, Haley was the wide receivers coach and passing game coordinator for the Dallas Cowboys. Haley helped develop quarterback [[Tony Romo]] and the Cowboys' passing offense, which centered around wide receivers [[Terry Glenn]] and [[Terrell Owens]].\n\n===Arizona Cardinals===\nIn 2007, Haley joined [[Ken Whisenhunt]]'s coaching staff for the Arizona Cardinals as the team's offensive coordinator. Haley did not start calling plays for the Cardinals until late in the season.<ref name=\"Chiefs hire Cardinals\"/> The Cardinals finished in the top half of the NFL in multiple offensive categories.\n\nUnder Haley\u2019s guidance, the Cardinals offense in 2008 was one of the league\u2019s most innovative and explosive units.<ref name=\"Haley named\"/> Arizona tied for third in the league in scoring, registering a franchise-record 427 points (26.7 ppg).<ref name=\"Haley named\"/> The Cardinals were fourth in total offense, averaging 365.8 yards per game.<ref name=\"Haley named\"/> Arizona was second in the league in passing offense (292.1 ypg) and ranked sixth in the NFL with 20.5 first downs per game.<ref name=\"Haley named\"/> The Cardinals finished the season with a 9\u20137 record and a playoff berth after winning the [[National Football Conference West Division|NFC West]] Division title. The Cardinals went on to appear in their first [[Super Bowl]] in franchise history after the team scored more than 30 points in each of its three playoff games.\n\nIn [[Super Bowl XLIII]], the Cardinals offense played the NFL's top-ranked Pittsburgh Steelers defense.<ref name=\"Steelers earn\">{{cite web | title=Steelers earn sixth Super Bowl victory in thriller over Cardinals | url=http://www.nfl.com/gamecenter/recap?game_id=54465&displayPage=tab_recap&season=2008&week=POST21 | date=February 1, 2009 | accessdate=February 6, 2009 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090410083740/http://www.nfl.com/gamecenter/recap?game_id=54465&displayPage=tab_recap&season=2008&week=POST21 | archive-date=April 10, 2009 | url-status=dead | df=mdy-all }}</ref> Trailing 17&ndash;7 at halftime, the Cardinals offense fought back after a 13-point deficit and led the game 23&ndash;20 with just over two minutes remaining.<ref name=\"Steelers earn\"/> The Cardinals lost 27&ndash;23 in the game's final seconds.<ref name=\"Steelers earn\"/>\n\n===Kansas City Chiefs===\nOn December 14, 2008, a last-minute loss to the [[San Diego Chargers]] led longtime Kansas City Chiefs General Manager [[Carl Peterson]] to abruptly announce his resignation the following day.  This paved the way toward the hiring of General Manager [[Scott Pioli]] on January 13, 2009.<ref name=\"Pioli to join\">{{cite web | title=Scott Pioli to join Kansas City Chiefs | url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=3830515 | publisher=ESPN.com | date=January 13, 2009 | accessdate=January 13, 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"Pioli named\">{{cite web | title=Scott Pioli named Kansas City Chiefs general manager | url=http://www.pitch.com/FastPitch/archives/2009/01/13/its-official-pioli-is-the-chiefs-new-gm | date=January 13, 2009 | accessdate=January 13, 2009 | publisher=Kansas City Chiefs}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> The decision to hire Pioli led to speculation that [[Herman Edwards]], who had been serving as the Chiefs' head coach since 2006, was not likely to return for 2009.<ref name=\"Pioli to join\"/> Edwards was fired on January 23, just five days after the Arizona Cardinals defeated the [[Philadelphia Eagles]] in the [[NFC Championship Game]].<ref name=\"Raising Arizona\">{{cite web | title=Raising Arizona: Late TD drive carries Cards to first Super Bowl | url=http://www.nfl.com/gamecenter/recap?game_id=54463&displayPage=tab_recap&season=2008&week=POST20 | publisher=NFL.com | date=January 18, 2009 | accessdate=February 6, 2009}}</ref> Leading up to [[Super Bowl XLIII]], Haley was repeatedly questioned about Kansas City and the possibilities of joining his former colleague Pioli.<ref name=\"Chiefs hire Cardinals\"/> Haley would later say that it was the day after the Super Bowl, which the Cardinals lost, that he heard his name mentioned for the Chiefs' coaching position.<ref name=\"Chiefs hire Cardinals\"/>\n\nIn the days after the Cardinals' appearance in Super Bowl XLIII, Haley was offered the head coaching position of the Chiefs.<ref name=\"Haley\">{{cite web | title=Source: Cards assistant tabbed to coach Chiefs | url=http://msn.foxsports.com/nfl/story/9187366/Sources:-Cards-assistant-tabbed-to-coach-Chiefs | last=Glazer | first=Jay | publisher=Fox Sports | date=February 5, 2009 | accessdate=February 6, 2009 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090207053139/http://msn.foxsports.com/nfl/story/9187366/Sources%3A-Cards-assistant-tabbed-to-coach-Chiefs | archive-date=February 7, 2009 | url-status=dead }}</ref> Haley accepted the position on February 6, 2009, and signed a four-year contract.<ref name=\"Haley named\"/><ref name=\"Chiefs hire Cardinals\">{{cite web | title=Chiefs hire Cardinals offensive coordinator Haley as coach | url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story?id=09000d5d80e9b58a&template=without-video-with-comments&confirm=true | author=Associated Press | date=February 6, 2009 | accessdate=February 6, 2009}}</ref> For his first coaching staff, Haley hired [[Joel Collier]], [[Gary Gibbs]], [[Steve Hoffman (American football)|Steve Hoffman]], [[Bill Muir]], [[Clancy Pendergast]], [[Pat Perles]], and [[Dedric Ward]] to unspecified positions on the Chiefs' 2009 coaching staff and retained [[Bob Bicknell]], [[Joe D\u2019Alessandris]], [[Chan Gailey]], [[Tim Krumrie]], [[Brent Salazar]], and [[Cedric Smith (American football)|Cedric Smith]] from [[Herm Edwards]]' staff.<ref name=\"staff moves\">{{cite web|title=Kansas City Chiefs announce coaching staff moves |url=http://kcchiefs.com/news/2009/02/17/kansas_city_chiefs_announce_coaching_staff_moves/ |date=February 17, 2009 |accessdate=February 17, 2009 |publisher=Kansas City Chiefs |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090221071902/http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2009/02/17/kansas_city_chiefs_announce_coaching_staff_moves |archivedate=February 21, 2009 }}</ref> Ward and Pendergast had previously served on the Cardinals' coaching staff with Haley.\n\nInitially there were doubts as to whether Chan Gailey would be retained under Haley's coaching staff, because Haley had just concluded a successful stint as offensive coordinator at Arizona. Haley initially expressed satisfaction in working with Gailey, saying, \"The more I work with the guy, the more I like him...\"{{Cite quote|date=November 2015}}  However, after the Chiefs lost their first three pre-season games partially due to an abysmal offensive performance, Haley reportedly refused to bow to Gailey's suggestion to once again install a [[spread offense]] similar to the one installed midway through the [[2008 Kansas City Chiefs season|2008]] season.  Gailey was relieved of duties and Haley assumed offensive play-calling duties throughout the rest of the season.<ref name=\"Gailey no longer\">{{cite web | title=Gailey no longer running Chiefs offense | url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=4434133 | publisher=ESPN.com | last=Clayton | first=John | date=August 31, 2009 | accessdate=August 31, 2009}}</ref>\n\nThe Chiefs lost their first five games under Haley in 2009. Haley won his first game as the Chiefs' head coach on October 18, 2009 beating the Washington Redskins 14\u20136.\n\nIn late October 2009 the Chiefs suspended starting running back [[Larry Johnson (running back)|Larry Johnson]] for one week in response to his public comments on [[Twitter]] where he questioned Haley's coaching abilities and for using homophobic slurs{{Clarify|reason=vague|date=November 2015}} when he addressed the media.<ref name=\"trouble\">{{cite web|url=http://blogs.nfl.com/2009/10/27/chiefs-suspend-johnson-indefinitely/ |title=Chiefs suspend Johnson indefinitely  |work=blogs.nfl.com |date=October 27, 2009 |accessdate=October 27, 2009}}</ref> Johnson's Twitter comments were: \"My father got more creditentials than most of these pro coaches\" [Sic]. That was followed by: \"My father played for the coach from \"Remember the Titans\". Our coach played golf. My father played for the Redskins briefly. Our coach. Nuthin.\" [Sic]<ref name=\"slur\">[http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=4596288 espn]</ref> When Johnson returned from his suspension, he was released.\n\nAfter Haley released Johnson, he led the Chiefs to their first two-game winning streak since the 2007 season with victories against the [[Oakland Raiders]] and Pittsburgh Steelers on November 15 and 22. The 27\u201324 victory over the Steelers\u2014the defending [[Super Bowl]] champions\u2014came in overtime.  The Chiefs ended their season with a victory against the [[Denver Broncos]] who were looking to clinch a Wild-Card playoff berth with a win.  This was the first Kansas City win at Denver since [[2000 Kansas City Chiefs season|2000]] and their first victory at [[Invesco Field at Mile High]] which opened in [[2001 NFL Season|2001]]. This concluded the Chiefs season with a 4\u201312 record, a two-win improvement from 2008.\n\nIn Haley's second season, the Chiefs won their first three games, including the season opener on [[Monday Night Football]] against the [[San Diego Chargers]], and were the last undefeated team remaining in the NFL before losing at Indianapolis in Week 5. Kansas City went on to win the AFC West for the first time since 2003.\n\nOn January 9, 2011, the Chiefs played the Baltimore Ravens at Arrowhead Stadium. The Chiefs lost the game 30\u20137 with [[Matt Cassel]] passing for 70 yards and 3 interceptions. The only touchdown was a 41-yard touchdown run by [[Jamaal Charles]].\n\nOn September 2, 2011, Haley elected to play his starters against the [[Green Bay Packers]] in the final preseason game of the year. Tight end [[Tony Moeaki]], a crucial piece of the team's 2011 offensive plans, injured his knee at the beginning of the second quarter and was ruled out for the remainder of the season. In a game played mostly by the Chiefs starters and the Packers' backups, the Chiefs lost, 20\u201319, leading many{{Who|date=November 2015}} to question Haley's decision to use his best players late into the game.\n\nDespite having lost several key players to injuries, on October 31, 2011, Haley led The Chiefs to a come-from-behind victory on ''Monday Night Football''. The win was KC's fourth in a row, which moved them into first place in the AFC West. It marked the first time in NFL history that a team which started 0\u20133 was leading its division by the halfway point of the season.\n\nChiefs starting quarterback Matt Cassel broke his hand during a week 11 game vs. the Denver Broncos. He was replaced by [[Tyler Palko]], and had surgery on the injured hand on November 14. On November 21, Cassel was placed on injured reserve, ending his season. Palko proved to be inadequate as a backup to a merely serviceable Cassel, leading many{{Who|date=November 2015}} to question how a team with legitimate playoff hopes entering the 2011 season had remained so thin at so many key positions during the off-season, especially at quarterback and safety, where the Chiefs' lack of depth was more than woeful.\n\nHaley was fired on December 12, 2011, after leading his team to a 5\u20138 record during the 2011 NFL season.<ref name=\"Firing\">{{cite web | title=Haley relieved of duties | url=http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/article-2/HALEY-RELIEVED-OF-DUTIES/9f2d029b-c450-48cb-9791-8038582a3270 | date=December 12, 2011 | accessdate=December 12, 2011 | publisher=Kansas City Chiefs | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120107051055/http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/article-2/HALEY-RELIEVED-OF-DUTIES/9f2d029b-c450-48cb-9791-8038582a3270 | archive-date=January 7, 2012 | url-status=dead }}</ref> The 2011 season began with three losses, including two blow-outs to Detroit and Buffalo. The team appeared to regroup, winning four straight games, before losing the next 5 of 6, including a complete team collapse in Haley's final game against the New York Jets. Late in that game Haley was flagged for an unsportsmanlike conduct penalty, allowing the Jets to complete a touchdown drive that ultimately put the game out of reach. After the loss, defensive coordinator [[Romeo Crennel]] was promoted to replace Haley.<ref>http://www.kansascity.com/2012/11/02/3897097/sam-mellinger-hold-your-nose-when.html</ref>\n\n===Pittsburgh Steelers===\nOn February 7, 2012, the Steelers announced that Haley would be the team's new offensive coordinator.  Haley grew up in the Pittsburgh suburb of [[Upper Saint Clair, Pennsylvania]], and his father was the Steelers' former personnel director.  He was the first offensive coordinator in 13 years to be hired from outside the organization.<ref>{{cite web | title=Haley \"excited\" to be new Steelers offensive coordinator| url=http://post-gazette.com/pg/12038/1208661-100.stm| work=[[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]]| publisher=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette| date=February 7, 2012| accessdate=February 7, 2012}}</ref> On January 17, 2018, the Steelers announced that Haley's contract, which had expired at the conclusion of the 2017 season, would not be renewed.<ref>{{cite web|title=Todd Haley will not return as Pittsburgh Steelers OC|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000907515/article/todd-haley-will-not-return-as-pittsburgh-steelers-oc|website=NFL.com}}</ref>\n\n===Cleveland Browns===\nOn January 22, 2018, Haley was hired by the [[Cleveland Browns]] as their offensive coordinator. On October 29, 2018, Haley was fired along with head coach [[Hue Jackson]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Haley is Browns' new offensive coordinator|url=https://www.cincinnati.com/story/sports/nfl/bengals/2018/01/23/haley-browns-new-offensive-coordinator-per-reports/1058657001/|website=Cincinnati.com}}</ref>\n\n===Riverview High School===\nOn February 14, 2020, Haley was hired as the offensive coordinator for the [[Riverview High School (Sarasota, Florida)|Riverview Rams]] in Sarasota, Florida.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Alper |first1=Josh |title=Todd Haley hired as offensive coordinator at a Sarasota high school |url=https://profootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2020/02/14/todd-haley-hired-as-offensive-coordinator-at-sarasota-high-school/ |website=ProFootballTalk |publisher=NBC Sports}}</ref>\n\n===Coaching style===\nHaley has been described as an aggressive coach and can be combative with players.<ref name=\"Chiefs hire Cardinals\"/><ref name=\"Players still\">{{cite web | title=Players still getting used to Haley's fiery style of coaching | url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story?id=09000d5d810eb4b0&template=without-video-with-comments&confirm=true | publisher=NFL.com | author=Associated Press | date=June 21, 2009 | accessdate=June 21, 2009}}</ref> During the 2008 NFC Championship Game against the Eagles, he had a first-half argument with quarterback [[Kurt Warner]], then a short blowup in full view of television cameras with wide receiver [[Anquan Boldin]] later in the game.<ref name=\"Chiefs hire Cardinals\"/> He also had a spat with [[Terrell Owens]] when he was the wide receivers coach in Dallas.<ref name=\"Chiefs hire Cardinals\"/> Defending his style, Haley said \"It's part of how I coach... It's part of how I motivate, and I like to think I've had some success doing it.\"<ref name=\"Chiefs hire Cardinals\"/>\n\n==Personal life==\nHaley has five children with his wife, Chrissy.<ref name=\"Haley named\"/>\n\nIn 2006, Haley filed a 1.5&nbsp;million-dollar lawsuit against [[McDonald's]] after his wife found a dead rat in her salad. The salad was purchased at a [[Southlake, Texas]] McDonald's restaurant while Haley was a member of the Dallas Cowboys coaching staff. His wife and their live-in babysitter began to eat before noticing the rat.  The case was settled out of court for a confidential amount.<ref name=\"mcdonalds\">{{cite web | title=I Smell a McRat | url=http://www.dallasobserver.com/2006-11-23/news/i-smell-a-mcrat/1/|work=Dallas Observer|publisher=Dallas Observer|accessdate=July 17, 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn December 31, 2017, a team spokesman stated Todd Haley was injured in a fall Sunday evening following the Steelers' Week 17 game.  It was initially reported that Haley had been injured in an altercation at a bar outside Heinz Field, however a spokesman for the Pittsburgh City Police stated that it was Haley's wife, Christine, who was involved in a \"minor scuffle\" at the bar Tequila Cowboy which was quickly ended.  Todd Haley was not involved nor injured in the incident.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Schad|first1=Tom|title=Pittsburgh police: Steelers OC Todd Haley OK; wife in bar scuffle|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nfl/steelers/2018/01/02/report-pittsburgh-steelers-oc-todd-haley-hurt-after-being-shoved-outside-bar/997741001/|publisher=USA Today|accessdate=January 3, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Head coaching record== Haley is trash.\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 95%; text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"|Team !! rowspan=\"2\"|Year !! colspan=\"5\"|Regular season !! colspan=\"4\"|Postseason\n|-\n!Won!!Lost!!Ties!!Win %!!Finish!! Won !! Lost !! Win % !! Result\n|-\n![[2009 Kansas City Chiefs season|KC]]||[[2009 NFL season|2009]]\n||4||12||0||.250||4th in AFC West|| - || - || - || -\n|-! style=\"background:#fdd;\"\n![[2010 Kansas City Chiefs season|KC]]||[[2010 NFL season|2010]]\n||10||6||0||.625||'''1st in AFC West'''|| 0 || 1 || .000 || <small>'''Lost to [[Baltimore Ravens]] in [[NFL playoffs, 2010-11|AFC Wild-Card Game]].'''</small>\n|-\n![[2011 Kansas City Chiefs season|KC]]||[[2011 NFL season|2011]]\n||5||8||0||.385||(Fired)|| - || - || - |||\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\"|Total<ref>[https://www.pro-football-reference.com/coaches/HaleTo0.htm Todd Haley Record, Statistics, and Category Ranks - Pro-Football-Reference.com<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>||19||26||0||||||0||1||.000||\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|American football|Biography}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120308201328/http://www.steelers.com/team/coaches/todd-haley/34e83eb9-ae2c-45f8-a9ba-37b2b8600b21 Pittsburgh Steelers profile]\n\t\n{{Kansas City Chiefs coach navbox}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Haley, Todd}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1967 births]]\n[[Category:Arizona Cardinals coaches]]\n[[Category:Chicago Bears coaches]]\n[[Category:Dallas Cowboys coaches]]\n[[Category:Kansas City Chiefs head coaches]]\n[[Category:New York Jets coaches]]\n[[Category:National Football League offensive coordinators]]\n[[Category:University of North Florida alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Florida alumni]]\n[[Category:Upper St. Clair High School alumni]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Atlanta]]\n[[Category:Cleveland Browns coaches]]\n[[Category:Pittsburgh Steelers coaches]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American football coach}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox NFL biography\n| name           = Todd Haley\n| image          = Todd Haley.jpg\n| image_size     = 240\n| alt            = Haley wearing a red Kansas City Chiefs sweatshirt and red Chiefs visor while autographing a Chiefs baseball cap\n| caption        = Haley with the Chiefs in 2009\n| current_team   = \n| position       =\n| birth_date     = {{Birth date and age|1967|2|28|mf=y}}\n| birth_place    = [[Atlanta, Georgia]]\n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n| high_school    = [[Upper St. Clair High School|Upper St. Clair]]<br>([[Upper St. Clair Township, Allegheny County, Pennsylvania|Upper St. Clair, Pennsylvania]])\n| college        = [[University of North Florida|North Florida]]\n| pastcoaching   = \n* [[New York Jets]] (1995\u20131996)<br>Scouting assistant\n* New York Jets (1997\u20132000)<br>Wide receivers coach\n* [[Chicago Bears]] (2001\u20132003)<br>Wide receivers coach\n* [[Dallas Cowboys]] (2004\u20132006)<br>Wide receivers coach\n* [[Arizona Cardinals]] (2007\u20132008)<br>Offensive coordinator\n* [[Kansas City Chiefs]] (2009\u20132011)<br>Head coach\n* [[Pittsburgh Steelers]] (2012\u20132017)<br>Offensive coordinator\n* [[Cleveland Browns]] (2018)<br>Offensive coordinator\n* [[Riverview High School (Sarasota, Florida)|Riverview High School]] (2020\u2013present)<br>Offensive coordinator\n| highlights     = \n| regular_record = {{Winning percentage|19|26|record=y}}\n| playoff_record = {{Winning percentage|0|1|record=y}}\n| overall_record = {{Winning percentage|19|27|record=y}}\n| pfrcoach       = HaleTo0\n}}\n\n'''Todd Haley''' (born February 28, 1967) is an [[American football]] coach who is the offensive coordinator for the [[Riverview High School (Sarasota, Florida)|Riverview High School]] football team. From 1997 to 2006, he had stints as the [[wide receiver]]s coach of the [[New York Jets]], [[Chicago Bears]], and [[Dallas Cowboys]]. He served as the offensive coordinator of the [[Arizona Cardinals]] from 2007 to 2008, the head coach of the [[Kansas City Chiefs]] from 2009 to 2011, the offensive coordinator of the [[Pittsburgh Steelers]] from 2012 to 2017, and the offensive coordinator of the [[Cleveland Browns]] in 2018, but he was fired in Week 8 of his first season with the team following a loss to his previous team, the Pittsburgh Steelers.\n\n==Early years==\nHaley was born on February 28, 1967, in [[Atlanta, Georgia]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Todd Haley named Kansas City Chiefs head coach |url=http://kcchiefs.com/news/2009/02/06/todd_haley_named_kansas_city_chiefs_head_coach/ |publisher=Kansas City Chiefs |date=February 6, 2009 |accessdate=February 6, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090209090923/http://kcchiefs.com/news/2009/02/06/todd_haley_named_kansas_city_chiefs_head_coach |archivedate=February 9, 2009 }}</ref> He is the son of [[Dick Haley]], formerly Director of Player Personnel for the Pittsburgh Steelers and New York Jets and also a former NFL cornerback.<ref name=\"Haley named\">{{cite web | title=Todd Haley named Kansas City Chiefs head coach |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090303204702/http://kcchiefs.com/news/2009/02/06/todd_haley_named_kansas_city_chiefs_head_coach |archivedate=March 3, 2009| url=http://kcchiefs.com/news/2009/02/06/todd_haley_named_kansas_city_chiefs_head_coach/ | publisher=Kansas City Chiefs | date=February 6, 2009 | accessdate=February 6, 2009}}</ref>\n\nAs a youth, Haley was a ball boy for the Steelers and attended Steelers training camps with his father.<ref name=\"Haley named\"/> Alongside his father, Haley would watch the Steelers' game and practice film.<ref name=\"Haley named\"/><ref name=\"new Chief in town\">{{cite web | title=Todd Haley is the new Chief in town | url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2009/writers/peter_king/02/06/chiefs/index.html | last=King | first=Peter | publisher=Sports Illustrated | date=February 6, 2009 | accessdate=February 6, 2009}}</ref> While his family was located in [[Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania]] for his father's profession, Haley attended [[Upper St. Clair High School]].<ref name=\"Haley named\"/> He went on to attend the [[University of Florida]] and [[University of Miami]], playing on the two schools' respective golf squads.<ref name=\"Haley named\"/> Haley graduated from the [[University of North Florida]] in 1991 with a bachelor's degree in communication.<ref name=\"Haley named\"/>\n\n==Coaching career==\n===New York Jets===\nHaley was hired by the New York Jets in 1995 and served as an assistant in the scouting department for two seasons. At the time, Haley's father Dick was working with the Jets as Director of Player Personnel.<ref name=\"new Chief in town\"/> In 1997, he was promoted to offensive assistant/quality control coach and worked closely with then-offensive coordinator [[Charlie Weis]]. From 1999 to 2000 Haley was the Jets' wide receivers coach, helping [[Keyshawn Johnson]] make his second [[Pro Bowl]] appearance. During his tenure with the Jets, Haley began his association with [[Scott Pioli]], who served as Director of Pro Personnel for the Jets from 1997 to 1999. Pioli later became the general manager of the Kansas City Chiefs and hired Haley as the team's head coach in 2009.\n\n===Chicago Bears===\nIn 2001, Haley joined the Chicago Bears as  wide receivers coach and served in the position until 2003.\n\n===Dallas Cowboys===\nFrom 2004 to 2006, Haley was the wide receivers coach and passing game coordinator for the Dallas Cowboys. Haley helped develop quarterback [[Tony Romo]] and the Cowboys' passing offense, which centered around wide receivers [[Terry Glenn]] and [[Terrell Owens]].\n\n===Arizona Cardinals===\nIn 2007, Haley joined [[Ken Whisenhunt]]'s coaching staff for the Arizona Cardinals as the team's offensive coordinator. Haley did not start calling plays for the Cardinals until late in the season.<ref name=\"Chiefs hire Cardinals\"/> The Cardinals finished in the top half of the NFL in multiple offensive categories.\n\nUnder Haley\u2019s guidance, the Cardinals offense in 2008 was one of the league\u2019s most innovative and explosive units.<ref name=\"Haley named\"/> Arizona tied for third in the league in scoring, registering a franchise-record 427 points (26.7 ppg).<ref name=\"Haley named\"/> The Cardinals were fourth in total offense, averaging 365.8 yards per game.<ref name=\"Haley named\"/> Arizona was second in the league in passing offense (292.1 ypg) and ranked sixth in the NFL with 20.5 first downs per game.<ref name=\"Haley named\"/> The Cardinals finished the season with a 9\u20137 record and a playoff berth after winning the [[National Football Conference West Division|NFC West]] Division title. The Cardinals went on to appear in their first [[Super Bowl]] in franchise history after the team scored more than 30 points in each of its three playoff games.\n\nIn [[Super Bowl XLIII]], the Cardinals offense played the NFL's top-ranked Pittsburgh Steelers defense.<ref name=\"Steelers earn\">{{cite web | title=Steelers earn sixth Super Bowl victory in thriller over Cardinals | url=http://www.nfl.com/gamecenter/recap?game_id=54465&displayPage=tab_recap&season=2008&week=POST21 | date=February 1, 2009 | accessdate=February 6, 2009 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090410083740/http://www.nfl.com/gamecenter/recap?game_id=54465&displayPage=tab_recap&season=2008&week=POST21 | archive-date=April 10, 2009 | url-status=dead | df=mdy-all }}</ref> Trailing 17&ndash;7 at halftime, the Cardinals offense fought back after a 13-point deficit and led the game 23&ndash;20 with just over two minutes remaining.<ref name=\"Steelers earn\"/> The Cardinals lost 27&ndash;23 in the game's final seconds.<ref name=\"Steelers earn\"/>\n\n===Kansas City Chiefs===\nOn December 14, 2008, a last-minute loss to the [[San Diego Chargers]] led longtime Kansas City Chiefs General Manager [[Carl Peterson]] to abruptly announce his resignation the following day.  This paved the way toward the hiring of General Manager [[Scott Pioli]] on January 13, 2009.<ref name=\"Pioli to join\">{{cite web | title=Scott Pioli to join Kansas City Chiefs | url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=3830515 | publisher=ESPN.com | date=January 13, 2009 | accessdate=January 13, 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"Pioli named\">{{cite web | title=Scott Pioli named Kansas City Chiefs general manager | url=http://www.pitch.com/FastPitch/archives/2009/01/13/its-official-pioli-is-the-chiefs-new-gm | date=January 13, 2009 | accessdate=January 13, 2009 | publisher=Kansas City Chiefs}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> The decision to hire Pioli led to speculation that [[Herman Edwards]], who had been serving as the Chiefs' head coach since 2006, was not likely to return for 2009.<ref name=\"Pioli to join\"/> Edwards was fired on January 23, just five days after the Arizona Cardinals defeated the [[Philadelphia Eagles]] in the [[NFC Championship Game]].<ref name=\"Raising Arizona\">{{cite web | title=Raising Arizona: Late TD drive carries Cards to first Super Bowl | url=http://www.nfl.com/gamecenter/recap?game_id=54463&displayPage=tab_recap&season=2008&week=POST20 | publisher=NFL.com | date=January 18, 2009 | accessdate=February 6, 2009}}</ref> Leading up to [[Super Bowl XLIII]], Haley was repeatedly questioned about Kansas City and the possibilities of joining his former colleague Pioli.<ref name=\"Chiefs hire Cardinals\"/> Haley would later say that it was the day after the Super Bowl, which the Cardinals lost, that he heard his name mentioned for the Chiefs' coaching position.<ref name=\"Chiefs hire Cardinals\"/>\n\nIn the days after the Cardinals' appearance in Super Bowl XLIII, Haley was offered the head coaching position of the Chiefs.<ref name=\"Haley\">{{cite web | title=Source: Cards assistant tabbed to coach Chiefs | url=http://msn.foxsports.com/nfl/story/9187366/Sources:-Cards-assistant-tabbed-to-coach-Chiefs | last=Glazer | first=Jay | publisher=Fox Sports | date=February 5, 2009 | accessdate=February 6, 2009 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090207053139/http://msn.foxsports.com/nfl/story/9187366/Sources%3A-Cards-assistant-tabbed-to-coach-Chiefs | archive-date=February 7, 2009 | url-status=dead }}</ref> Haley accepted the position on February 6, 2009, and signed a four-year contract.<ref name=\"Haley named\"/><ref name=\"Chiefs hire Cardinals\">{{cite web | title=Chiefs hire Cardinals offensive coordinator Haley as coach | url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story?id=09000d5d80e9b58a&template=without-video-with-comments&confirm=true | author=Associated Press | date=February 6, 2009 | accessdate=February 6, 2009}}</ref> For his first coaching staff, Haley hired [[Joel Collier]], [[Gary Gibbs]], [[Steve Hoffman (American football)|Steve Hoffman]], [[Bill Muir]], [[Clancy Pendergast]], [[Pat Perles]], and [[Dedric Ward]] to unspecified positions on the Chiefs' 2009 coaching staff and retained [[Bob Bicknell]], [[Joe D\u2019Alessandris]], [[Chan Gailey]], [[Tim Krumrie]], [[Brent Salazar]], and [[Cedric Smith (American football)|Cedric Smith]] from [[Herm Edwards]]' staff.<ref name=\"staff moves\">{{cite web|title=Kansas City Chiefs announce coaching staff moves |url=http://kcchiefs.com/news/2009/02/17/kansas_city_chiefs_announce_coaching_staff_moves/ |date=February 17, 2009 |accessdate=February 17, 2009 |publisher=Kansas City Chiefs |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090221071902/http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2009/02/17/kansas_city_chiefs_announce_coaching_staff_moves |archivedate=February 21, 2009 }}</ref> Ward and Pendergast had previously served on the Cardinals' coaching staff with Haley.\n\nInitially there were doubts as to whether Chan Gailey would be retained under Haley's coaching staff, because Haley had just concluded a successful stint as offensive coordinator at Arizona. Haley initially expressed satisfaction in working with Gailey, saying, \"The more I work with the guy, the more I like him...\"{{Cite quote|date=November 2015}}  However, after the Chiefs lost their first three pre-season games partially due to an abysmal offensive performance, Haley reportedly refused to bow to Gailey's suggestion to once again install a [[spread offense]] similar to the one installed midway through the [[2008 Kansas City Chiefs season|2008]] season.  Gailey was relieved of duties and Haley assumed offensive play-calling duties throughout the rest of the season.<ref name=\"Gailey no longer\">{{cite web | title=Gailey no longer running Chiefs offense | url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=4434133 | publisher=ESPN.com | last=Clayton | first=John | date=August 31, 2009 | accessdate=August 31, 2009}}</ref>\n\nThe Chiefs lost their first five games under Haley in 2009. Haley won his first game as the Chiefs' head coach on October 18, 2009 beating the Washington Redskins 14\u20136.\n\nIn late October 2009 the Chiefs suspended starting running back [[Larry Johnson (running back)|Larry Johnson]] for one week in response to his public comments on [[Twitter]] where he questioned Haley's coaching abilities and for using homophobic slurs{{Clarify|reason=vague|date=November 2015}} when he addressed the media.<ref name=\"trouble\">{{cite web|url=http://blogs.nfl.com/2009/10/27/chiefs-suspend-johnson-indefinitely/ |title=Chiefs suspend Johnson indefinitely  |work=blogs.nfl.com |date=October 27, 2009 |accessdate=October 27, 2009}}</ref> Johnson's Twitter comments were: \"My father got more creditentials than most of these pro coaches\" [Sic]. That was followed by: \"My father played for the coach from \"Remember the Titans\". Our coach played golf. My father played for the Redskins briefly. Our coach. Nuthin.\" [Sic]<ref name=\"slur\">[http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=4596288 espn]</ref> When Johnson returned from his suspension, he was released.\n\nAfter Haley released Johnson, he led the Chiefs to their first two-game winning streak since the 2007 season with victories against the [[Oakland Raiders]] and Pittsburgh Steelers on November 15 and 22. The 27\u201324 victory over the Steelers\u2014the defending [[Super Bowl]] champions\u2014came in overtime.  The Chiefs ended their season with a victory against the [[Denver Broncos]] who were looking to clinch a Wild-Card playoff berth with a win.  This was the first Kansas City win at Denver since [[2000 Kansas City Chiefs season|2000]] and their first victory at [[Invesco Field at Mile High]] which opened in [[2001 NFL Season|2001]]. This concluded the Chiefs season with a 4\u201312 record, a two-win improvement from 2008.\n\nIn Haley's second season, the Chiefs won their first three games, including the season opener on [[Monday Night Football]] against the [[San Diego Chargers]], and were the last undefeated team remaining in the NFL before losing at Indianapolis in Week 5. Kansas City went on to win the AFC West for the first time since 2003.\n\nOn January 9, 2011, the Chiefs played the Baltimore Ravens at Arrowhead Stadium. The Chiefs lost the game 30\u20137 with [[Matt Cassel]] passing for 70 yards and 3 interceptions. The only touchdown was a 41-yard touchdown run by [[Jamaal Charles]].\n\nOn September 2, 2011, Haley elected to play his starters against the [[Green Bay Packers]] in the final preseason game of the year. Tight end [[Tony Moeaki]], a crucial piece of the team's 2011 offensive plans, injured his knee at the beginning of the second quarter and was ruled out for the remainder of the season. In a game played mostly by the Chiefs starters and the Packers' backups, the Chiefs lost, 20\u201319, leading many{{Who|date=November 2015}} to question Haley's decision to use his best players late into the game.\n\nDespite having lost several key players to injuries, on October 31, 2011, Haley led The Chiefs to a come-from-behind victory on ''Monday Night Football''. The win was KC's fourth in a row, which moved them into first place in the AFC West. It marked the first time in NFL history that a team which started 0\u20133 was leading its division by the halfway point of the season.\n\nChiefs starting quarterback Matt Cassel broke his hand during a week 11 game vs. the Denver Broncos. He was replaced by [[Tyler Palko]], and had surgery on the injured hand on November 14. On November 21, Cassel was placed on injured reserve, ending his season. Palko proved to be inadequate as a backup to a merely serviceable Cassel, leading many{{Who|date=November 2015}} to question how a team with legitimate playoff hopes entering the 2011 season had remained so thin at so many key positions during the off-season, especially at quarterback and safety, where the Chiefs' lack of depth was more than woeful.\n\nHaley was fired on December 12, 2011, after leading his team to a 5\u20138 record during the 2011 NFL season.<ref name=\"Firing\">{{cite web | title=Haley relieved of duties | url=http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/article-2/HALEY-RELIEVED-OF-DUTIES/9f2d029b-c450-48cb-9791-8038582a3270 | date=December 12, 2011 | accessdate=December 12, 2011 | publisher=Kansas City Chiefs | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120107051055/http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/article-2/HALEY-RELIEVED-OF-DUTIES/9f2d029b-c450-48cb-9791-8038582a3270 | archive-date=January 7, 2012 | url-status=dead }}</ref> The 2011 season began with three losses, including two blow-outs to Detroit and Buffalo. The team appeared to regroup, winning four straight games, before losing the next 5 of 6, including a complete team collapse in Haley's final game against the New York Jets. Late in that game Haley was flagged for an unsportsmanlike conduct penalty, allowing the Jets to complete a touchdown drive that ultimately put the game out of reach. After the loss, defensive coordinator [[Romeo Crennel]] was promoted to replace Haley.<ref>http://www.kansascity.com/2012/11/02/3897097/sam-mellinger-hold-your-nose-when.html</ref>\n\n===Pittsburgh Steelers===\nOn February 7, 2012, the Steelers announced that Haley would be the team's new offensive coordinator.  Haley grew up in the Pittsburgh suburb of [[Upper Saint Clair, Pennsylvania]], and his father was the Steelers' former personnel director.  He was the first offensive coordinator in 13 years to be hired from outside the organization.<ref>{{cite web | title=Haley \"excited\" to be new Steelers offensive coordinator| url=http://post-gazette.com/pg/12038/1208661-100.stm| work=[[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]]| publisher=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette| date=February 7, 2012| accessdate=February 7, 2012}}</ref> On January 17, 2018, the Steelers announced that Haley's contract, which had expired at the conclusion of the 2017 season, would not be renewed.<ref>{{cite web|title=Todd Haley will not return as Pittsburgh Steelers OC|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000907515/article/todd-haley-will-not-return-as-pittsburgh-steelers-oc|website=NFL.com}}</ref>\n\n===Cleveland Browns===\nOn January 22, 2018, Haley was hired by the [[Cleveland Browns]] as their offensive coordinator. On October 29, 2018, Haley was fired along with head coach [[Hue Jackson]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Haley is Browns' new offensive coordinator|url=https://www.cincinnati.com/story/sports/nfl/bengals/2018/01/23/haley-browns-new-offensive-coordinator-per-reports/1058657001/|website=Cincinnati.com}}</ref>\n\n===Riverview High School===\nOn February 14, 2020, Haley was hired as the offensive coordinator for the [[Riverview High School (Sarasota, Florida)|Riverview Rams]] in Sarasota, Florida.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Alper |first1=Josh |title=Todd Haley hired as offensive coordinator at a Sarasota high school |url=https://profootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2020/02/14/todd-haley-hired-as-offensive-coordinator-at-sarasota-high-school/ |website=ProFootballTalk |publisher=NBC Sports}}</ref>\n\n===Coaching style===\nHaley has been described as an aggressive coach and can be combative with players.<ref name=\"Chiefs hire Cardinals\"/><ref name=\"Players still\">{{cite web | title=Players still getting used to Haley's fiery style of coaching | url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story?id=09000d5d810eb4b0&template=without-video-with-comments&confirm=true | publisher=NFL.com | author=Associated Press | date=June 21, 2009 | accessdate=June 21, 2009}}</ref> During the 2008 NFC Championship Game against the Eagles, he had a first-half argument with quarterback [[Kurt Warner]], then a short blowup in full view of television cameras with wide receiver [[Anquan Boldin]] later in the game.<ref name=\"Chiefs hire Cardinals\"/> He also had a spat with [[Terrell Owens]] when he was the wide receivers coach in Dallas.<ref name=\"Chiefs hire Cardinals\"/> Defending his style, Haley said \"It's part of how I coach... It's part of how I motivate, and I like to think I've had some success doing it.\"<ref name=\"Chiefs hire Cardinals\"/>\n\n==Personal life==\nHaley has five children with his wife, Chrissy.<ref name=\"Haley named\"/>\n\nIn 2006, Haley filed a 1.5&nbsp;million-dollar lawsuit against [[McDonald's]] after his wife found a dead rat in her salad. The salad was purchased at a [[Southlake, Texas]] McDonald's restaurant while Haley was a member of the Dallas Cowboys coaching staff. His wife and their live-in babysitter began to eat before noticing the rat.  The case was settled out of court for a confidential amount.<ref name=\"mcdonalds\">{{cite web | title=I Smell a McRat | url=http://www.dallasobserver.com/2006-11-23/news/i-smell-a-mcrat/1/|work=Dallas Observer|publisher=Dallas Observer|accessdate=July 17, 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn December 31, 2017, a team spokesman stated Todd Haley was injured in a fall Sunday evening following the Steelers' Week 17 game.  It was initially reported that Haley had been injured in an altercation at a bar outside Heinz Field, however a spokesman for the Pittsburgh City Police stated that it was Haley's wife, Christine, who was involved in a \"minor scuffle\" at the bar Tequila Cowboy which was quickly ended.  Todd Haley was not involved nor injured in the incident.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Schad|first1=Tom|title=Pittsburgh police: Steelers OC Todd Haley OK; wife in bar scuffle|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nfl/steelers/2018/01/02/report-pittsburgh-steelers-oc-todd-haley-hurt-after-being-shoved-outside-bar/997741001/|publisher=USA Today|accessdate=January 3, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Head coaching record==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 95%; text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"|Team !! rowspan=\"2\"|Year !! colspan=\"5\"|Regular season !! colspan=\"4\"|Postseason\n|-\n!Won!!Lost!!Ties!!Win %!!Finish!! Won !! Lost !! Win % !! Result\n|-\n![[2009 Kansas City Chiefs season|KC]]||[[2009 NFL season|2009]]\n||4||12||0||.250||4th in AFC West|| - || - || - || -\n|-! style=\"background:#fdd;\"\n![[2010 Kansas City Chiefs season|KC]]||[[2010 NFL season|2010]]\n||10||6||0||.625||'''1st in AFC West'''|| 0 || 1 || .000 || <small>'''Lost to [[Baltimore Ravens]] in [[NFL playoffs, 2010-11|AFC Wild-Card Game]].'''</small>\n|-\n![[2011 Kansas City Chiefs season|KC]]||[[2011 NFL season|2011]]\n||5||8||0||.385||(Fired)|| - || - || - |||\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\"|Total<ref>[https://www.pro-football-reference.com/coaches/HaleTo0.htm Todd Haley Record, Statistics, and Category Ranks - Pro-Football-Reference.com<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>||19||26||0||||||0||1||.000||\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|American football|Biography}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120308201328/http://www.steelers.com/team/coaches/todd-haley/34e83eb9-ae2c-45f8-a9ba-37b2b8600b21 Pittsburgh Steelers profile]\n\t\n{{Kansas City Chiefs coach navbox}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Haley, Todd}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1967 births]]\n[[Category:Arizona Cardinals coaches]]\n[[Category:Chicago Bears coaches]]\n[[Category:Dallas Cowboys coaches]]\n[[Category:Kansas City Chiefs head coaches]]\n[[Category:New York Jets coaches]]\n[[Category:National Football League offensive coordinators]]\n[[Category:University of North Florida alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Florida alumni]]\n[[Category:Upper St. Clair High School alumni]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Atlanta]]\n[[Category:Cleveland Browns coaches]]\n[[Category:Pittsburgh Steelers coaches]]\n", "name_user": "97.85.216.217", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Todd_Haley"}
